<br />
The term D-Day was used for many invasions, landings, etc not just the invasion of Normandy.<br />
<br />
There are literally dozens of "d-days". June 6, 1944 was only one of them and that date was changed several times because of weather. The ships were on their way to Normandy on June 5 and turned back because of weather so the Normandy invasion could have taken place June 5 instead but didn&#39;t, hence the term d-day, the date it actually takes starts.<br />
<br />
And no, they don&#39;t have a term for when it actually ends but you could say VE day was the day it ended which means the battle took almost a year to fight so I suppose anyone who landed at Normandy, in the first wave or the 37th, 3 weeks later, could claim being a D-Day survivor.  lol <br><BR><font size=1>14:51 11-11-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Serpent</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">d-day was more than one day... <br><BR><font size=1>10:25 11-11-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">This is splitting hairs of course but if you want to talk casualties, Iwo Jima had around 600 dead and over 17,000 wounded. A sick number considering Iwo Jima is a tiny little speck of an island on the Pacific Ocean.<br />
<br />
If you tally the entire war in France, well, that&#39;s a whole different story and time line. <br><BR><font size=1>10:24 11-11-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">Pearl Harbor wasn&#39;t a battle? Come on Patrick, that&#39;s absurd. It was the first battle of the Pacific war. Our definition of battle might differ but one armed force attacking another is most definitely a battle.<br />
<br />
D-Day wasn&#39;t 6 weeks either. It was June 6, 1944 and June 6 only. The invasion of France wasn&#39;t 6 weeks either, it was quite a bit longer than that.<br />
<br />
D-Day is called the greatest invasion in history because of it&#39;s historical significance, the beginning of the liberation of France and Western Europe but history books are very selective aren&#39;t they? In 1943, the Allies landed on Sicily with more divisions than they did on D-Day. The allies had 3 million men under Eisenhower&#39;s command but they all didn&#39;t land that day, in fact many of them were never landed in Normandy, they landed in Southern France.<br />
<br />
Pearl Harbor obviously wasn&#39;t an invasion, it was an air attack by the Japanese on mostly unsuspecting US Navy and Army personnel. 1,104 men on the USS Arizona alone were killed during the attack and hundreds more on the Oklahoma and many civilians were killed.<br />
<br />
It doesn&#39;t make either battle more important but D-Day was far from the deadliest battle. It was an overwhelming invasion by the Allies on a weakened German army. It was only a matter of time once we landed and the battle was never in doubt. Salerno, Anzio, Tarawa, Betio, Leyte, Iwo Jima were far costlier in terms of number of men landed and killed in respect to the number of troops opposing the landing. Tarawa was the deadliest invasion in US history.<br />
<br />
Be that as it may, it doesn&#39;t diminish any of the accomplishments nor courage by any of our troops, I just want to make sure that people understand that Di-Day might have been the most historically significant but certainly not the most difficult or costliest battle of World War II.  <br><BR><font size=1>10:21 11-11-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=3300">Shadow 13™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">hmm i was unclear.  my grandfather was stationed there throughout the 24-day long battle.  the casualty listing for "d-day" i quoted i believe is for just june 6, 1944. <br><BR><font size=1>22:49 11-10-2007</font><BR><BR><hr><img align="right" src="http://www.decktech.net/memberimages/3300rst.jpg"><br>Ryan French<br>Rebel Strike Team founder<br><i>"I&#39;m a total whore for torture porn."</i> - Patrick Sullivan</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=3300">Shadow 13™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Normandy#Omaha_Beach">where my grandfather was</a> on d-day.<br />
