by D-day we&#39;re talking the Battle of Normandy, btw, which was june 6-30, 1944.<br />
<br />
"American casualties at Omaha on D-Day numbered around 3,000 out of 34,000 men, most in the first few hours." - that wiki.  that&#39;s just omaha beach, one of a half dozen or more beaches where the invasion force landed. <br><BR><font size=1>22:44 11-10-2007</font><BR><BR><hr><img align="right" src="http://www.decktech.net/memberimages/3300rst.jpg"><br>Ryan French<br>Rebel Strike Team founder<br><i>"I&#39;m a total whore for torture porn."</i> - Patrick Sullivan</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">that is the most ridiculous death toll for D-Day I&#39;ve ever seen. The actual number is staggering. <br />
<br />
Plus Pearl harbour wasn&#39;t a battle. <br />
<br />
The two are very different.  <br><BR><font size=1>16:23 11-10-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Total Jackass</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">The Axis:  Italy, Germany, Russia <br><BR><font size=1>17:52 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Bluto</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Did we give up when the Germans bombed Pearl Harbor? <br><BR><font size=1>17:52 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=3300">Shadow 13™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">pearl harbor was 4 hours.  D-day was 6 weeks.  i think that&#39;s somewhere close to his reasoning.<br />
<br />
but really, i think it was just that the only plates you see from ww2 are the pearl harbor ones.  there was a lot more to ww2 than just pearl harbor. <br><BR><font size=1>17:23 11-09-2007</font><BR><BR><hr><img align="right" src="http://www.decktech.net/memberimages/3300rst.jpg"><br>Ryan French<br>Rebel Strike Team founder<br><i>"I&#39;m a total whore for torture porn."</i> - Patrick Sullivan</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">A quick search finds the following:<br />
<br />
Casualties at Pearl Harbor, December 7, 1941:<br />
<br />
2,300+ dead plus 68 civilians<br />
<br />
D-Day June 6, 1944:<br />
<br />
2,500 Allied deaths- 1,465 Americans. (340 Canadians)<br />
<br />
Either way, I&#39;d be more than proud to say I survived either one of those battles.<br />
<br />
D-Day was not a choice at all. Men didn&#39;t volunteer. You can make the claim that some men wanted to be the first one&#39;s to land in France for the historical signifigance but I would wager that most were scared shytless and rightfully so.<br />
<br />
Neither battle is more or less important than the other. Pearl Harbor is the attack that brought us into the war. Naturally, we declared war on Japan and in turn, Hitler, the idiot, declared war on the United States which was a huge mistake as American involvement in Europe was still very much in doubt. I think we would have gotten involved eventually anyway but who knows. <br><BR><font size=1>12:46 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=617">Max of Tat™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont"><blockquote><i>However, being in D-Day was by DECISION. You actually went out of your way to participate in this historic event and put yourself intentionally in harm&#39;s way. Something to be proud of. True heroes. </i></blockquote><br />
<br />
How is that "decision" any different than the one the sailors made when they choose to be in the Navy?<br />
<br />
If I recall, the Allies didn&#39;t ask for volunteers for D-day and only those that wanted to make history decided to be there. Those soldiers where "in the right place at the right time" to be a part of it because they were ordered to be there. Both sets of survivors participated in historic battles that helped shaped the world. I wouldn&#39;t dare to compare which of those two is more important.<br />
<br />
- Enrique <br><BR><font size=1>12:25 11-09-2007</font><BR><BR><a href="http://www.decktech.net/vs/decks/chesslobbyframe.html">DeckTech Chess Player</a><br>My job is to bring pictures of semi-naked women to DeckTech. I love my job.</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">He probably thinks (and rightly so, in my opinion) that D-Day was more of an ordeal than Pearl Harbour. chances of surviving D-Day were far lower too and it was a monumental effort and historical event. Pearl Harbour had more victims than heroes, for instance. <br />
<br />
I&#39;m guessing his line of reasoning is something like that. It&#39;s like if someone was in the towers on 9-11 and survived. I don&#39;t think they should put 9-11 survivor on their license plate. They were just in the right place at the right time. <br />
<br />
hmmm... cuz here&#39;s the thing, Pearl Harbour is a tragedy, in some ways. So surviving it and putting it on your license plate is just about being at the right place at the right time. That&#39;s mostly why that person is alive. However, being in D-Day was by DECISION. You actually went out of your way to participate in this historic event and put yourself intentionally in harm&#39;s way. Something to be proud of. True heroes.  <br><BR><font size=1>11:30 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">I&#39;ve seen them before, rarely.<br />
<br />
I don&#39;t know why anyone would be upset about a Pearl Harbor Survivor plate.<br />
<br />
A soldier who served in world war II as a cook at a base in Nebraska should be proud of himself and anyone else who served. Everyone was important to the war effort, not just one&#39;s who served in a large, famous battle. If I were a Pearl Harbor attack survivor, I&#39;d be pretty proud. He must have a reason to not like those. <br><BR><font size=1>11:23 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">wow. That&#39;s awesome. D-Day Survivot actually means something too. <br />
<br />
Hey, I never heard of the Pearl Harbour survivor plates. Who gets those? What do they mean? They were at the base when it got attacked and survived? <br><BR><font size=1>10:38 11-09-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=3300">Shadow 13™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">my grandfather was in the Navy during WW2, he piloted one of the LC boats ferrying wounded back from Omaha Beach on D-Day.  he has license plate holders that say "D-Day Survivor" because he thinks all the "Pearl Harbor Survivor" plates are ridiculous.<br />
<br />
he then transfered to to the Army and fought in Korea 5 yrs later. <br><BR><font size=1>17:20 11-08-2007</font><BR><BR><hr><img align="right" src="http://www.decktech.net/memberimages/3300rst.jpg"><br>Ryan French<br>Rebel Strike Team founder<br><i>"I&#39;m a total whore for torture porn."</i> - Patrick Sullivan</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont"><blockquote><i>i think remembering thousands of people who died for a war, and reciting a poem about a graveyard from the war, is pretty damn anti-war </i></blockquote><br />
<br />
Yeah, but it&#39;s indirectly anti-war. The purpose of the poem and remembering tens of thousands that have died isn&#39;t to be anti-war. It&#39;s to remember, honour, respect and give thanks to those that have died. The anti-war aspect is totally indirect and secondary. <br />
<br />
<br />
Mike, yeah I&#39;m pretty sure the 3rd reich had the shortest life of all German reichs. It&#39;s like a total disaster compared to how long the other two lasted. One, in particular, lasted like forever.  <br><BR><font size=1>08:15 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">The people that died as a result of the wars over time are very well worth rememberance. Doesn&#39;t matter how you do it, it just matters that they be remembered.<br />
<br />
My great uncle, Michael, died in France in 1917 I believe, fighting for the United States. His family had immigrated from Austria maybe 20 years or so before that to Brooklyn, NY, and my grandmother was born in 1910 so she was 7 when she found out her brother died. I can&#39;t even imagine what that is like. Somehow, the majority of my family on both sides has avoided all of the wars over the years. My grandfather was in his 30&#39;s when WWII started but was exempt somehow because he worked for Firestone making tires so he was essential to the war effort in another way. My father was to young for WW2 and Korea and to old for Vietnam. One of my uncles fought in Korea and that&#39;s about it. I have no war stories for you.<br />
<br />
Me? I have always been fascinated by World War II. The shear magnitude of it is almost beyond comprehension, the number of people who fought and died is unbelievable. The Holocaust where distant relatives were murdered by the Nazis or simply killed as a result of war in Austria, Germany, and Russia has always interested me but records are so rare and I don&#39;t know that I would really want to find out exactly what happened to them.<br />
<br />
It&#39;s kind of wierd having lineage of Jewish and German ancestors.<br />
<br />
Anyway, Canada&#39;s contribution in both wars was huge given the population differences. My memory of WWI is fuzzy but I do know, a Canadian, Roy Brown, shot down the Red Baron and was one of the leading fighter aces of that war when the life expectancy of a pilot was maybe 20-24 HOURS of flying time. Incredible.<br />
<br />
The sacrfices made by all countries should always be remembered. If not for many people, we might be speaking German right now. Hitler&#39;s dream was for the 3rd Reich to last 1,000 years and if he wasn&#39;t so arrogant and left the miltary strategy to the military, things might be much different.(a 2 pronged attack on Russia instead of a 3 pronged attack made a huge difference as well as declaring war on the United States)<br />
<br />
No countries contribution to either war can be forgotten, not even the Germans, Hungarians, or any of the so called "bad guys". Remember, they follow the orders of the morons in charge, just like our troops do today. Support the troops, protest the politicians!<br />
<br />
I love the story about Burger&#39;s grandfather meeting up with a Russian soldier and having a drink.<br />
<br />
Another, more well known story is, during 1918 I believe, before the armistice and in the doldrums of trench warfare, a British soldier and German soldier met in no man&#39;s land and organized a football(soccer) match, not so much as for fun but as much to say how much they hated what they were doing to each other in a bloodbath of battle and that they didn&#39;t hate each other. They played their match, returned to the trenches and the armistice was signed not long after. <br><BR><font size=1>08:05 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Serpent</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">i think remembering thousands of people who died for a war, and reciting a poem about a graveyard from the war, is pretty damn anti-war <br><BR><font size=1>00:08 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><TD colspan='2'><font class="bfont"><A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php'>Back to Topics List</A></font></TD></TD></TABLE><P><B>Showing last 30 posts! </b><form action='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php'><input type='hidden' name='showmore' value='1'><input type='hidden' name='id' value=8896><input type='Submit'  value=' Show all Posts '></form><form action='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php'><input type='hidden' name='showmore' value='2'><input type='hidden' name='id' value=8896><input type='Submit'  value=' Show Next 30 Posts '></form><p><font class="bfont"><b>You must be a member to add topics to this list.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/heroclix/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></div></div><script language='javascript'>function quoteboard(quotetext){document.buzzboardform.comments.value = '<i>'+quotetext+'</i><p>';}</script> 			
